==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Galilean
<hw>Gal`i*le"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining
to Galileo; <as>as, the <ex>Galilean</ex> telescope</as>. See
<er>Telescope</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Galilean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Galilean
<hw>Gal`i*le"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Galilaeus</ets>, fr. <ets>Galilaea</ets> Galilee, Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>galil⟦eacute⟧en</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or relating to
Galilee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Galilean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Galilean
<hw>Gal`i*le"an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or
inhabitant of Galilee, the northern province of Palestine under the
Romans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Jewish Hist.)</fld> <def>One of the party among the
Jews, who opposed the payment of tribute to the Romans; -- called also
<altname>Gaulonite</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A Christian in general; -- used as a term of
reproach by Muslims and Pagans.</def> <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Galilee</ent>⟦br⟧
